observations.recommendation:
Appoint or designate a General Service Officer who shall specifically take custody of all the properties of the LGU and prepare and maintain stock cards and property cards for it; create an inventory committee that shall perform a physical inventory of all properties of the Municipality and submit to the Audit Team the Report on Physical count of PPE (RCPPE) and Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI);

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to maintain and update Inventories and PPE Ledger Cards for each category of inventory and PPE and to conduct periodic reconciliation of balances thereof with that of the GSO records; and 

Require the Municipal Accountant to compute the depreciation on the equipment accounts and make the necessary adjustment on the affected accounts.

Appropriate fund for the titling of all land;  

Direct the Municipal Assessor’s Office to facilitate the preparation of documentary requirements to secure the Transfer Certificate of Title of the land owned by the Municipality; 

Require the Municipal Accountant to submit the necessary supporting documents for the purchase of lot, such as Deed of Absolute Sale registered with the Register of Deeds, Certified Photocopy of Tax Clearance from Assessor’s office and Transfer Certificate of Title (TCT), Original Certificate Title certified as true copy by the Register of Deeds and Tax Declaration (TD) certified as true copy by the Assessor's Office; and

Ensure that the Land accounts recorded in the books, which were not supported with TCT and other legal documents of ownership, should be properly disclosed in the Notes to Financial Statements.

Record transactions in the cashbooks promptly and in order of occurrence including specifying the date of deposit for collections and liquidation of cash advances to maintain accurate records and prevent errors;

Balance, rule and close at the end of the day the cashbooks and foot and close the books and certify the balances in writing at the end of each month;

Require the OIC Municipal Treasurer to maintain a cashbook for each type of cash advance and each type of fund;

Require the Collecting Officers to establish and maintain Cashbooks to document their collections and remittances in accordance with the prescribed manner outlined in the Cash Examination Manual; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant and accountable officers to reconcile their records regularly or at least once every quarter to establish the correct balance of accountability of the AOs at the earliest time possible.

Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

Direct the General Services Officer-Designate to maintain the Local Road Inventory and Road Map, and to keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and their components; and

Require the concerned personnel to attend training and seminar on Local Road Asset Management to ensure compliance with the transitory provision under COA Circular 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Formally create a General Services Office with a clear mandate to manage all municipal assets;
Appoint a permanent General Service Officer with the appropriate authority and responsibility to oversee the asset management function;
Create an inventory committee comprised of representatives from relevant departments who shall perform a physical inventory of all properties of the Municipality and define clear roles and responsibilities for committee members, including periodic reviews and audits of asset records;
Develop and enforce a policy that mandates an annual physical count of all property, plant, and equipment; and
Reconcile physical counts with the recorded asset balances, and promptly investigate any discrepancies.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Require the Municipal Accountant to compute depreciation expense and the related accumulated depreciation in all their asset accounts and make the necessary adjusting entries to correct balances of the affected accounts;
Implement periodic reviews to ensure that depreciation is computed, recorded, and reviewed in accordance with IPSAS/PPSAS 17 and applicable COA circulars;
Reassess whether fully depreciated assets that remain in use should continue to be carried at a zero or near-zero net value, or if any impairment reversals or revaluations are warranted; and
Investigate the cause of over depreciation for “Other Transportation Equipment” to correct any misapplications of the depreciation method or useful life estimates.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Direct the HRMO and Municipal Accountant to expedite the reconciliation of records with the GSIS to come up with the updated service records;
Direct the AAO to observe prompt submission of ARA to GSIS whenever there are changes in members’ data to ensure timely updating of the GSIS database and prevent inaccuracies in billing statements;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to identify employees affected by the unreconciled balances of the GSIS and Pag-Ibig and validate the amounts with official payroll records; and
Upon confirmation, the Municipal Treasurer should remit the unpaid contributions and loan amortizations immediately to prevent penalties and interest charges.

Direct the Municipal Accountant to record transactions that are cash advances in nature with the appropriate Advances account(s) applicable and not as outright expenses. Make the necessary adjusting entries; 

Submit DVs and supporting documents for unsubmitted accounts of the Municipal Treasurer summarized in Annex E; and

Acting Municipal Treasurer to prepare Report of Disbursements (ROD) for the succeeding cash advances.

Ensure that the purpose of cash advances are on the face of the disbursement vouchers and that they are duly supported with complete documents at the time of grant and ensure that cash advances for payroll fund shall be equal to the net amount of the payroll for the pay period;

Discontinue the practice of disbursing funds through cash advances to pay for the Municipality’s operating expenses but instead pay directly under the name of the payees, concerned employees and suppliers, ensuring that the transactions of the LGU are always supported with complete documentation that would ascertain their propriety and validity;

Refrain from granting multiple cash advances to the Acting Municipal Treasurer and ensure that his previous cash advance has been liquidated before granting additional cash advance.

Direct the Municipal Treasurer to prepare the Report of Checks Issued (RCI) with checks presented chronologically and numerically, ensuring that all checks released or unreleased to claimants are included, along with the cancelled/voided checks; 

The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to strictly comply with the requirements under COA Circular No. 92-389 and Section 32, Chapter 2, Volume II of NGAS Manual to maintain sound internal control in the disbursement of government funds through properly accomplishing the Disbursement Vouchers, particularly on the numbering and proper listing of the supporting documents on the face of the DV and the perforation of the paid Disbursement Vouchers and payrolls, including all supporting documents, to avoid their reuse; and

The BAC and End-user to properly and completely accomplish relevant procurement documents such as PR, RFQ, Abstract of Quotation and PO and provide the necessary and relevant specifications of the items to be procured in unambiguous terms for all future procurement projects to serve as reference during inspection and acceptance of deliveries by management.

Direct the BAC to submit the required supporting documents to substantiate their claims on honoraria;

Discontinue the inclusion of the Municipal Treasurer as member of the Technical Working Group (TWG) pursuant to DOF Department Order No. 042-2019, otherwise, subsequent payments will be disallowed in audit; and

Observe strict compliance with implementing rules and regulations of procurement law on the qualifications of Bids and Awards Committee (BAC), BAC Secretariat and Technical Working Group (TWG) and the prescribed rates per DBM Budget Circular No. 2007-5A.

Require the Bids and Awards Committee to strictly comply with the provisions of RA 9184 in the conduct of public bidding and awarding of the contracts;

Direct the BAC members, BAC secretariat and TWG to internalize the different rules and regulations set forth by RA 9184;

Require the end-users to attach a copy of APP of the projects contracted in order to guide management in the procurement of goods and infrastructure projects and furnish COA of the same for audit/evaluation purposes;

Post all results of bidding and related information in the PhilGEPS website;

Instruct the BAC to submit the contract within the prescribed period; and

BAC Secretariat to ensure that bidders submit complete eligibility requirements and all documentary requirements before signing the contract.

Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that withholding taxes are deducted from payments of honoraria to avoid penalties;

Increase manpower or assign employees in the Municipal Accountant’s Office, in case of heavy workloads, to function as a pre-audit and to ensure that taxes are correctly withheld; and

Refund the overpayment and remit it to the BIR.

Strictly follow the perpetual inventory method in recording and accounting of inventories for distribution;

Conduct physical count of unused inventories for the recognition of inventories accounts reported without balances in the books; and

Prepare and maintain the required forms, subsidiary records and periodic reports in relation to receipt and issuance of inventories for distribution.

Strictly follow the perpetual inventory method in recording and accounting of inventories for distribution;

Conduct physical count of unused inventories for the recognition of inventories accounts reported without balances in the books; and

Prepare and maintain the required forms, subsidiary records and periodic reports in relation to receipt and issuance of inventories for distribution.

Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and General Services Officer with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;

Direct the General Services Officer-Designate to maintain the Local Road Inventory and Road Map, and to keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and their components; and

Require the concerned personnel to attend training and seminar on Local Road Asset Management to ensure compliance with the transitory provision under COA Circular 2015-008 dated November 23, 2015.

