Post all results of bidding and related information in the PhilGEPS website;
Instruct the BAC to submit the contract within the prescribed period; and
BAC Secretariat to ensure that bidders submit complete eligibility requirements and all documentary requirements before signing the contract.

Require the Supply Officer and RHU to coordinate and come up with a clear defined responsibility for proper inventory-taking, reporting, supervision and disposition of the transferred drugs, medicines, medical supplies from DOH, PHO and the Commission on Population and Development;

Require the Supply Officer to inform the Municipal Accountant and furnish her with the receipt of asset for her to recognize it in the books basing on the PTRs issued by the DOH;

Ensure that the receiving officer requires that PTRs are duly approved and value of items received are indicated properly otherwise coordinate with the DOH and PHO source agency for that matter; and

Require preparation of Distribution and Utilization Report for accounting, evaluation and documentation purposes;

Require the submission of lacking documentary requirements for travels by all personnel indicated in Annex G in accordance with COA Circular No. 2021-001, otherwise direct refund of travels claimed;

Adjust prior year’s transactions and reclassify other erroneous debits to the account to the appropriate account for proper accounting in conformity with Volume III of the NGAS Manual for LGUs;

Justify why payments for registration fees to various organizations in excess of the allowable P2,000 per day participation fee were granted, otherwise require the concerned organizations/associations to issue government official receipts; 

Direct the refund of excessive DTE of P2,700;

Stop payment of gasoline and fuel cost as transportation expense and cost of actual meals for travel claims by employees. Adhere strictly to EO No. 77 for computation of allowable travel claims;

Require revision of IT’s by those who claimed for actual costs of gasoline and actual meals and recompute for allowable traveling expense using the current rate to establish if traveling expenses claimed were not excessive, otherwise, direct refund of the excess; and

Require justification for travels where use of car hire was allowed.

Direct the Municipal Accountant to explain payments of monetization to employees several times in a year and ensure that disbursement vouchers are always supported with complete documents as enumerated in Section 5.14 of COA Circular 2012-001 and to retain at least five days of their vacation leave credits after monetization;

Require the Municipal HRMO and the personnel concerned to submit immediately the lacking supporting documents; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to clarify rates used in the computation of taxes withheld and the adjustments made as claimed for verification purposes.

The Municipal Accountant to maintain special account in the General Fund and prepare financial statements for the (i) water works system and (ii) 20% Development Fund, supported by a separate set of subsidiary ledgers for each development project charged to the said fund, whether current or continuing;

The Sangguniang Bayan to enact ordinance exclusive for the administration and operation of Maigo Water Utilities; and

The Municipal Accountant to correct the proper account used for waterworks system from Other Service Income to Waterworks System Fees under business income.

Recommendations:
We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:
Direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to strictly verify the remittances of the collectors and ensure that all collections and accountable forms are fully accounted;
In case of heavy workload, direct the Acting Municipal Treasurer to designate a Liquidating Officer who will focus on monitoring and ensuring that cash collections of Collecting Officers are remitted intact daily and are fully accounted;
Direct the collectors to remit intact on a daily basis their collection to the Acting Municipal Treasurer or Liquidating Officer.

We recommended that the Revenue Collecting Officer:
a.) Cause the responsible persons who issued IOUs, “vales” or other forms of promissory notes or to whom cash disbursements were made to return the amount used from collections.
b.) Produce the missing funds and deposit it to its appropriate treasury of the agency and credited to the particular accounts to which the said money belongs;
c.) Discontinue the use of collections as cash disbursement to defray expenses and stop the practice of spending public funds without an existing appropriation;
d.) Refrain from using the collections to accommodate IOUs, “vales” and other forms of promissory notes;
e.) Deposit intact all her collections to the designated bank on a daily basis pursuant to Section 7 and Section 8 of COA Circular No. 92-382 dated July 3, 1992
f.) The Municipal Treasurer submit a report showing the breakdown of the deposits made and identifying to which collections or fund transfers these deposits pertain.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive to:

Direct the accountable officer to remit collections intact daily in consonance with Section 69 of P.D. 1445; and the Municipal Treasurer to strictly adhere the provision of COA Circular 92-382 dated July 3, 1992 to avoid possible misappropriation of asset;

Demand immediate deposits of the remaining undeposited amount;

Stop payment of expenses out of the cash collections and comply with the COA rules and regulations pertaining to it.

We recommended that the Municipal Treasurer:

Cause the Collecting Officer to update the cashbook and record collections and deposits on a daily basis for easy determination, monitoring and verification of balances;

Cause the Collecting Officer to maintain separate cashbook for each fund handled in accordance with what the National Government Accounting System Manual for LGUs prescribes.

We recommended the Local Chief Executive to:

a.) Cause the Municipal Treasurer to liquidate immediately her unliquidated cash advances for payroll and operating expenses;

b.) Ensure that the Accountable Officer which are granted cash advance must liquidate her cash advances within the required period provided in item 5.1 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;

c.) Withheld the salary or any money payable to the Municipal Treasurer until the cash advances has been fully liquidated and settled pursuant to item 5.1 and 9.3.2 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;

d.) Recording of Liquidation should be made on a per cash advance basis and not on a monthly basis;

e.) Record the ATM Payroll in a separate Subsidiary Ledger;

f.) Maintain separate cashbooks for salaries, wages, allowances, etc and for operating expenses. The Accountable Officer shall record the transactions in the prescribed cashbook daily in accordance with Item 6 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997.

Recommendations:
We recommended the Local Chief Executive to:
Cause the Municipal Treasurer to liquidate immediately her unliquidated cash advances for payroll and operating expenses;
Ensure that the Accountable Officer which are granted cash advance must liquidate her cash advances within the required period provided in item 5.1 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;
Withheld the salary or any money payable to the Municipal Treasurer until the cash advances has been fully liquidated and settled pursuant to item 5.1 and 9.3.2 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997;
Recording of Liquidation should be made on a per cash advance basis and not on a monthly basis;
Record the ATM Payroll in a separate Subsidiary Ledger;
Maintain separate cashbooks for salaries, wages, allowances, etc and for operating expenses. The Accountable Officer shall record the transactions in the prescribed cashbook daily in accordance with Item 6 of COA Circular No. 97-002 dated February 10, 1997.
Management Comment:
Liquidation were already submitted to Accounting Office. With regards to payroll and other vouchers, the processing of the vouchers for the Mayor’s Office is very slow causing the advances not liquidated on time.
Cashbook is already maintained by the Municipal Treasurer on her cash collections and adopt the other audit recommendations.
